{"nbformat":4,"nbformat_minor":0,"metadata":{"colab":{"provenance":[],"authorship_tag":"ABX9TyPfc5bgXQBdtcAfjG/RmD3D"},"kernelspec":{"name":"python3","display_name":"Python 3"},"language_info":{"name":"python"}},"cells":[{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["# Performance Measures For Classifier\n","\n","Evaluating a classifier is often significantly trickier than evaluating a regressor."],"metadata":{"id":"RRXhrwybBPqc"}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["## 1 Measuring Accuracy Using Cross-Validation\n","\n","A good way to evaluate a model is to use cross-validation, just as you did in the machine learnig sample project.\n","\n","Let's use the `cross_val_score()` function to evaluate your LinearSVC model\n","using K-fold cross-validation, with five folds. K-fold crossvalidation means splitting the training set into K-folds (in this case, five), then making\n","predictions and evaluating them on each fold using a model trained on the\n","remaining folds.\n","\n","![cv](https://scikit-learn.org/stable/_images/grid_search_cross_validation.png)"],"metadata":{"id":"OZJQa_6PBY0c"}},{"cell_type":"code","execution_count":2,"metadata":{"colab":{"base_uri":"https://localhost:8080/"},"id":"xeVf_0LyBGGI","executionInfo":{"status":"ok","timestamp":1772486162342,"user_tz":300,"elapsed":3335,"user":{"displayName":"Ben Xue","userId":"08600776733826581408"}},"outputId":"001eed25-9119-4f49-ec40-6de3c9490d40"},"outputs":[{"output_type":"execute_result","data":{"text/plain":["array([0.96666667, 0.96666667, 1.        , 0.86666667, 0.96666667])"]},"metadata":{},"execution_count":2}],"source":["from sklearn.model_selection import cross_val_score\n","from sklearn.datasets import load_iris\n","from sklearn.pipeline import Pipeline\n","from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler\n","from sklearn.svm import LinearSVC\n","import numpy as np\n","\n","iris = load_iris()\n","X = iris[\"data\"][:,(2,3)] # petal length, petal width\n","y=(iris[\"target\"]==2).astype(np.float64) # Iris-Virginica\n","\n","svm_clf = Pipeline([\n","    (\"scalar\",StandardScaler()),\n","    (\"linear_svc\", LinearSVC(C=1, loss=\"hinge\")) #‘hinge’ is the standard SVM loss\n","])\n","\n","cross_val_score(svm_clf, X, y, cv=5, scoring = \"accuracy\")"]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["In this example, we are using the \"Accuracy\" measure, which evluates the percentage of correct predictions. However, when you are dealing with an imbalanced dataset (lots of zeros and few ones or vice versa), this measure can give you an illusion. Consider a sample with one y=1 observation and 99 y=0 observations, a dumb classifier that predicts 0 all the time can have a 99% accuracy."],"metadata":{"id":"JOvuqFl0DlTi"}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["## 2 Confusion Matrix\n","\n","A much better way to evaluate the performance of a classifier is to look at the **confusion matrix**. The general idea is to count the number of times instances of class A are classified as class B. For example, to know the number of times the classifier confused 0s with 1s, you would look in the 1st row and 2nd column of the confusion matrix.\n","\n","To compute the confusion matrix, you first need to have a set of predictions, so they can be compared to the actual targets. You can use the cross_val_predict() function.\n","\n","Just like the cross_val_score() function, cross_val_predict() performs K-fold\n","cross-validation, but instead of returning the evaluation scores, it returns the predictions made on each test fold. This means that you get a clean prediction for each instance in the training set (“clean” meaning that the prediction is made by a model that never saw the data during training)."],"metadata":{"id":"ziB7ofyYEzIv"}},{"cell_type":"code","source":["from sklearn.model_selection import cross_val_predict\n","y_pred = cross_val_predict(svm_clf, X, y, cv=5)"],"metadata":{"id":"S5bjZNLnFQEl","executionInfo":{"status":"ok","timestamp":1772486164535,"user_tz":300,"elapsed":112,"user":{"displayName":"Ben Xue","userId":"08600776733826581408"}}},"execution_count":3,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["Now you are ready to get the confusion matrix using the confusion_matrix() function. Just pass it the target classes (y) and the predicted classes\n","(y_pred)."],"metadata":{"id":"uDYF_JM0FoLm"}},{"cell_type":"code","source":["from sklearn.metrics import confusion_matrix\n","confusion_matrix(y, y_pred)"],"metadata":{"colab":{"base_uri":"https://localhost:8080/"},"id":"5lGc0kMsFtOm","executionInfo":{"status":"ok","timestamp":1772486166162,"user_tz":300,"elapsed":7,"user":{"displayName":"Ben Xue","userId":"08600776733826581408"}},"outputId":"420dd36b-fcdf-4476-f833-c1d682845304"},"execution_count":4,"outputs":[{"output_type":"execute_result","data":{"text/plain":["array([[97,  3],\n","       [ 4, 46]])"]},"metadata":{},"execution_count":4}]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["Each row in a confusion matrix represents an actual class, while each column represents a predicted class. The first row of this matrix considers non-Iris-Virginicas (the negative class): 97 of them were correctly classified as 0s (**true negatives**), while the remaining 3 were wrongly classified as 1s (**false positives**). The second row considers the Iris-Virginicas (the positive class): 4 were wrongly classified as 0s (**false negatives**), while the remaining 46 were correctly classified as 1s (**true positives**).\n","\n","A perfect classifier would have only true positives and true negatives, so its confusion matrix would have nonzero values only on its main diagonal (top left to bottom right).\n","\n","The confusion matrix gives you a lot of information, but sometimes you may prefer a more concise metric. An interesting one to look at is the **accuracy of the positive predictions**; this is called the **precision** of the classifier (i.e. the conditional accuracy in the 2nd column)\n","\n","$$precision=\\frac{TP}{TP+FP} = \\frac{46}{46+3}$$\n","\n","TP is the number of true positives, and FP is the number of false positives.\n","\n","A trivial way to have perfect precision is to make one single positive prediction and ensure it is correct (precision = 1/1 = 100%). This would not be very useful since the classifier would ignore all but one positive instance. So precision is typically used along with another metric named **recall**, also called **sensitivity** or **true positive rate (TPR)**: this is the ratio of positive instances that are correctly detected by the classifier. (i.e. the conditional accuracy in the 2nd row)\n","\n","$$recall=\\frac{TP}{TP+FN} = \\frac{46}{46+4}$$\n","\n"],"metadata":{"id":"9V52qQ4UF04Q"}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["## 3 Precision and Recall\n","\n","Scikit-Learn provides several functions to compute classifier metrics, including precision and recall:\n","\n"],"metadata":{"id":"omlsNewFH3mZ"}},{"cell_type":"code","source":["from sklearn.metrics import precision_score, recall_score\n","precision_score(y, y_pred), recall_score(y, y_pred)\n"],"metadata":{"colab":{"base_uri":"https://localhost:8080/"},"id":"Vr_DqeaZH-MK","executionInfo":{"status":"ok","timestamp":1772486171271,"user_tz":300,"elapsed":10,"user":{"displayName":"Ben Xue","userId":"08600776733826581408"}},"outputId":"dc3b0d65-0102-4621-a7f5-03ebcb438ca6"},"execution_count":5,"outputs":[{"output_type":"execute_result","data":{"text/plain":["(0.9387755102040817, 0.92)"]},"metadata":{},"execution_count":5}]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["It is often convenient to combine precision and recall into a single metric called the **F1 score**, in particular if you need a simple way to compare two classifiers. The F1 score is the harmonic mean of precision and recall. Whereas the regular mean treats all values equally, the harmonic mean gives much more weight to low values. As a result, the classifier will only get a high F1 score if both recall and precision are high.\n","\n","$$F_1 = \\frac{2}{\\frac{1}{precision}+\\frac{1}{recall}}$$"],"metadata":{"id":"ohn-ijobIOta"}},{"cell_type":"code","source":["from sklearn.metrics import f1_score\n","f1_score(y, y_pred)"],"metadata":{"colab":{"base_uri":"https://localhost:8080/"},"id":"flxllnOmIko0","executionInfo":{"status":"ok","timestamp":1772486175672,"user_tz":300,"elapsed":8,"user":{"displayName":"Ben Xue","userId":"08600776733826581408"}},"outputId":"68b2960c-05da-4f3a-9a05-78f59e5ebbd8"},"execution_count":6,"outputs":[{"output_type":"execute_result","data":{"text/plain":["0.9292929292929293"]},"metadata":{},"execution_count":6}]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["> The F1 score *favors classifiers that have similar precision and recall*.\n","\n","Unfortunately, given a fixed model, you can't have both higher precision and recall by simply shifting the decision boundry (you can, of course, increase both scores by choosing better models, which means tweaking the boundry). This is called the precision/recall tradeoff.\n","\n","## 4 Precision/Recall Tradeoff\n","\n","To understand this tradeoff, let's look at how the LinearSVC makes its classification decisions. For each instance, it computes a score based on a decision function, and if that score is greater than a threshold, it assigns the instance to the positive class, or else it assigns it to the negative class. By shifting the decision threshold (boundry) to the positive direction, you make fewer positive predictions and more negative prediction. Since precision is the positive column conditional accuracy, its value will go up (the blury observations are now in the negative column). At the same time, the model predicts fewer true positives and allocates more blury observations to the false negatives (2nd row 1st column). Hence the row conditioanl accuracy (recall) will go down.\n","\n","Scikit-Learn does not let you set the threshold directly, but it does give you access to the decision scores that it uses to make predictions. Instead of calling the classifier's `predict()` method, you can call its `decision_function()` method, which returns a signed \"distance\" to the default boundry for each instance. You can then make predictions based on those scores using any threshold you want:"],"metadata":{"id":"vIGWBb_9IpXm"}},{"cell_type":"code","source":["y_scores = cross_val_predict(svm_clf, X, y, cv=5, method=\"decision_function\") # generate decision scores"],"metadata":{"id":"0VDWJc9mLhnK","executionInfo":{"status":"ok","timestamp":1772486177554,"user_tz":300,"elapsed":25,"user":{"displayName":"Ben Xue","userId":"08600776733826581408"}}},"execution_count":7,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"code","source":["from sklearn.metrics import precision_recall_curve\n","import matplotlib.pyplot as plt\n","\n","precisions, recalls, thresholds = precision_recall_curve(y, y_scores) # use decision scores\n","plt.plot(thresholds, precisions[:-1], \"b--\", label=\"Precision\") # precisions and recall have one more element than thresholds\n","plt.plot(thresholds, recalls[:-1], \"g-\", label=\"Recall\")\n","plt.legend()\n","plt.show()"],"metadata":{"colab":{"base_uri":"https://localhost:8080/","height":430},"id":"_VfHJV3wMKxs","executionInfo":{"status":"ok","timestamp":1772486179165,"user_tz":300,"elapsed":227,"user":{"displayName":"Ben Xue","userId":"08600776733826581408"}},"outputId":"3dc94c02-17e8-4b7a-9c4c-c1e6d814405e"},"execution_count":8,"outputs":[{"output_type":"display_data","data":{"text/plain":["<Figure size 640x480 with 1 Axes>"],"image/png":"\n"},"metadata":{}}]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["Another way to visualize the precision/recall tradeoff is to plot precision directly against recall.\n"],"metadata":{"id":"s7xldCusO_Ae"}},{"cell_type":"code","source":["plt.plot(precisions[:-1], recalls[:-1])\n","plt.xlabel(\"precision\")\n","plt.ylabel(\"recall\")\n","plt.show()"],"metadata":{"colab":{"base_uri":"https://localhost:8080/","height":449},"id":"rU1HaHNfPk40","executionInfo":{"status":"ok","timestamp":1772486182926,"user_tz":300,"elapsed":92,"user":{"displayName":"Ben Xue","userId":"08600776733826581408"}},"outputId":"5c10d755-512c-447d-d689-2f50ee976828"},"execution_count":9,"outputs":[{"output_type":"display_data","data":{"text/plain":["<Figure size 640x480 with 1 Axes>"],"image/png":"\n"},"metadata":{}}]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["## 5 The ROC Curve\n","\n","The **receiver operating characteristic (ROC)** curve is another common tool used with binary classifiers. It is very similar to the precision/recall curve, but instead of plotting precision versus recall, the ROC curve plots the **true positive rate** (another name for recall) against the **false positive rate**. The FPR is the ratio of negative instances that are incorrectly classified as positive (first row conditional inaccuracy). It is equal to one minus the true negative rate, which is the ratio of negative instances that are correctly classified as negative. The TNR is also called specificity. Hence the ROC curve plots sensitivity (recall) versus 1 - specificity."],"metadata":{"id":"fidYuzYZO4NG"}},{"cell_type":"code","source":["from sklearn.metrics import roc_curve\n","\n","fpr, tpr, thresholds = roc_curve(y, y_scores) # use decision scores\n","\n","plt.plot(fpr, tpr, linewidth=2)\n","plt.plot([0, 1], [0, 1], 'k--') # dashed diagonal\n","plt.ylabel(\"TPR (-> accuracy in the 2nd row)\")\n","plt.xlabel(\"FPR (-> inaccuracy in the 1st row)\")\n","plt.show()"],"metadata":{"colab":{"base_uri":"https://localhost:8080/","height":449},"id":"SCkcH0poQxvs","executionInfo":{"status":"ok","timestamp":1772486186553,"user_tz":300,"elapsed":168,"user":{"displayName":"Ben Xue","userId":"08600776733826581408"}},"outputId":"6673660b-0908-4543-da06-9c86d0c8ff86"},"execution_count":10,"outputs":[{"output_type":"display_data","data":{"text/plain":["<Figure size 640x480 with 1 Axes>"],"image/png":"\n"},"metadata":{}}]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["Once again there is a tradeoff: the higher the recall (TPR), the more false positives (FPR) the classifier produces. The dotted line represents the ROC curve of a purely random classifier; a good classifier stays as far away from that line as possible (toward the top-left corner).\n","\n","One way to compare classifiers is to measure the area under the curve (AUC). A perfect classifier will have a ROC AUC equal to 1, whereas a purely random classifier will have a ROC AUC equal to 0.5. Scikit-Learn provides a function to compute the ROC AUC:"],"metadata":{"id":"s516dIGcRBuq"}},{"cell_type":"code","source":["from sklearn.metrics import roc_auc_score\n","roc_auc_score(y, y_scores) # use decision scores"],"metadata":{"colab":{"base_uri":"https://localhost:8080/"},"id":"XH_tDFiqR8XY","executionInfo":{"status":"ok","timestamp":1772486200622,"user_tz":300,"elapsed":4,"user":{"displayName":"Ben Xue","userId":"08600776733826581408"}},"outputId":"d94002d9-699c-4344-ce53-b8c5ba27a2f9"},"execution_count":11,"outputs":[{"output_type":"execute_result","data":{"text/plain":["np.float64(0.9945)"]},"metadata":{},"execution_count":11}]}]}